Lesson 5 - Responsible AI Use and Hands-On Genealogical Applications

Goal: Understand AI safety considerations and practice hands-on genealogical activities
Duration: 25-35 minutes
Prerequisites: Completion of Lessons 1-4
What You'll Learn: Safety practices, privacy considerations, bias awareness, and six practical AI applications for genealogy

Why AI Safety Matters for Genealogists

As powerful as AI tools are for genealogical research, it's crucial to use them responsibly and understand their limitations. Family history research deals with sensitive personal information, requires high accuracy standards, and often involves irreplaceable historical documents.



‚ö†Ô∏è Critical Reality Check: AI tools can "hallucinate"‚Äîproviding incorrect, nonsensical, or completely fabricated information that sounds plausible. This is why verification through reliable, defensible sources is not optional‚Äîit's essential for maintaining the integrity of your family history research.

Essential Safety Considerations

‚úÖVerification & Accuracy

  • Always verify AI information against primary sources
  • Cross-reference using multiple AI tools or traditional methods
  • Treat AI as an assistant, not an infallible expert
  • Apply "garbage in, garbage out" principle‚Äîquality input yields quality output

üîíPrivacy Protection

  • Avoid entering sensitive information about living people
  • Don't share DNA match lists or personal details
  • Use temporary/private chats when available
  • Focus on deceased individuals (generally safer)

‚öñÔ∏èBias Awareness

  • AI inherits training data biases including gender and racial assumptions
  • Question default assumptions in AI responses
  • Specify inclusive language when needed
  • Be aware of historical context in AI interpretations

Best Practices for Responsible AI Use

üéØ Core Principles

‚úÖ Do

  • Use AI as a tool to enhance traditional research
  • Break complex problems into manageable pieces
  • Document when and how AI assistance was used
  • Start with simple, specific tasks
  • Maintain control of your research process
  • Disclose AI assistance in reports

‚ùå Don't

  • Replace traditional genealogical methods entirely
  • Accept AI responses without verification
  • Share private information about living relatives
  • Assume AI responses are always accurate
  • Ignore potential biases in AI suggestions
  • Use AI outputs as primary source citations
Documentation Best Practice: When using AI assistance in your research, maintain a log noting which AI tool was used, what prompts were given, and how the responses were verified. This creates an audit trail for your research methodology.

üìù Transcription Activity

Purpose: Decipher hard-to-read handwritten records from old wills, letters, or census images.

üì∏ Upload Area
Upload a screenshot of handwritten text here
(Old letter, will, census record, etc.)
Example Prompt:
"Transcribe this handwritten text, noting any uncertain words in square brackets [like this]. If text is completely illegible, mark as [illegible]. Maintain the original line breaks and formatting as much as possible."
üéØ Practice Checklist:
Verification Tip: Always compare AI transcriptions with the original document. AI may struggle with faded text, unusual handwriting styles, or archaic letter forms.

üìã Summarization Activity

Purpose: Condense lengthy documents like probate records, newspaper articles, or pension files into manageable forms.

Example Prompt:
"Summarize this historical newspaper article, highlighting key individuals, dates, and locations. Focus on information that would be useful for genealogical research. Present the summary in bullet points."
üéØ Practice Checklist:

üîç Information Extraction Activity

Purpose: Pull specific details like names, dates, places, and relationships from various records.

Example Prompt:
"Extract all names and their relationships to the deceased from this obituary. Organize the information in a table with columns for: Name, Relationship, Location (if mentioned), and Additional Details."
Pro Tip: Information extraction is particularly useful for obituaries, census records, and passenger lists where multiple names and relationships are listed in paragraph form.
üéØ Practice Checklist:

üèõÔ∏è Historical Context Activity

Purpose: Get information about historical events, social customs, and migration patterns relevant to your ancestors' lives.

Example Prompt:
"What was life like for a coal miner in Pennsylvania in the 1890s? Include common challenges, daily routines, typical wages, working conditions, and family life. Focus on information that would help understand my ancestor's experience."
üéØ Practice Checklist:

üóìÔ∏è Research Planning Activity

Purpose: Brainstorm new approaches for "brick wall" problems or suggest potential sources and strategies.

Example Prompt:
"I'm researching an ancestor whose movements between 1870 and 1880 are unclear. He appears in Ohio in 1870 but shows up in Kansas in 1880 with no trail between. Suggest a research strategy and relevant record types that might help track this movement."
Remember: AI-generated research strategies are starting points. Always adapt suggestions to your specific situation and available resources.
üéØ Practice Checklist:

üñºÔ∏è Image Analysis Activity

Purpose: Identify time periods based on clothing or hairstyles in photographs, or extract details from maps.

üì∏ Upload Area
Upload an old family photo or historical map here
(Family portrait, landscape photo, historical map, etc.)
Example Prompt:
"Describe the people and setting in this image. Based on clothing styles, hairstyles, and photographic techniques, estimate the time period. Note any details that might help with genealogical research such as locations, occupations, or social status indicators."
Analysis Focus:



Best Results: AI image analysis works best with clear, high-quality photos. For very old or damaged photos, AI may struggle with accuracy.

üéØ Lesson Summary

  • Safety First: Always verify AI information and protect privacy of living individuals
  • Bias Awareness: AI tools can inherit biases from training data‚Äîbe critically aware
  • Enhancement, Not Replacement: Use AI to enhance traditional genealogical methods
  • Six Practical Applications: Transcription, summarization, extraction, context, planning, and analysis
  • Documentation Matters: Keep records of AI assistance used in your research
  • Start Simple: Begin with straightforward tasks and build your AI skills gradually
